This research work investigates magnetic abrasive finishing of selective laser melted 316L stainless steel. Seven samples with various slope angles were printed and their surface were systematically characterized regarding surface roughness and topography. Magnetic abrasive finishing (MAF) was developed to polish the as-printed surfaces.The surface roughness evolution and material removal were well recorded and analysed.Besides,the material removal rate of MAF process was modelled. The following conclusions could be drawn:

(1) The SLM strategy is a dominant factor for the initial surface roughness which features an increase with the slope angle till ${ { 6 0 } ^ { \circ } }$ followed by a decrease due to larger step length leading to reduction of the percentage of unmolten particles;   
(2) The developed magnetic abrasive finishing method can effectively remove most partially bonded particles and balling defects,which requires substantial mechanical work exerted on the material removal in a sizable volume rather than a simply polishing process to achieve a glossy surface;   
(3) After magnetic abrasive finishing,a maximum decrease of $7 5 . 7 \%$ in surface roughness Ra was achieved and the average reduction of $\mathrm { R p }$ is almost twice as that of Rv;   
(4)As the developed magnetic abrasive finishing method is not devised based on a deterministic material removal mechanism,small amplitudes of surface irregularities will be removed most effectively.

Thus, the surface roughness after finishing follows the similar trend found in the initial surface roughness of the as-built samples;

